[Well, both WPV1 and cVDPV2 and cVDPV1 continue to be identified in cases and in environmental samples and samples of contacts of recently confirmed acute flaccid paralysis (AFP) cases. One can choose to be pessimistic about this observation or look at the possible bright side -- improved surveillance in high-risk areas (areas with suboptimal vaccination coverages) is finding more cases. In other words -- "Seek and ye shall find" (as opposed to the corollary "Don't look and it ain't there") is the operative. The worrisome observation is the occurrence of continued circulation of the cVDPVs over wider geographic expanses -- now involving 3 separate states in Nigeria, 3 separate provinces in Papua New Guinea, and multiple provinces in the Democratic Republic of the Congo. And as a reminder, the affected areas include areas of civil unrest, where it has been difficult for the public health infrastructure to enter safely for vaccination and surveillance activities.

An additional noteworthy observation is that for the past 2 years, the number of cases related to cVDPVs has outnumbered the number of WPV-associated cases in the world. The risk-to-benefit pendulum is now switching -- in countries that have interrupted WPV transmission, the risk from the use of OPV in areas with low vaccination coverages is now outweighing the risk of WPV encounter. - Mod.MPP

